        you can simply take the code, customize it and deploy the desired solution on your servers.
        We're constantly improving the capabilities of the dashboard and releasing it as open
        source, so watch for new features.
        </p>
        <%= image_tag 'dashboard-panel.png', class: 'bordered' %>
        <p>
        </p>
        <a class="button-add" href="http://lelylan.github.io/devices-dashboard-ng/">Get started with Lelylan Dashboard &rarr;</a>
        <a class="button-add" href="http://github.com/lelylan/devices-dashboard-ng/">Get source code on Github &rarr;</a>
      </div>
      <div class="right small">
        <%= image_tag 'companies/customizations.png' %>
      </div>
      <div class="clearfix"></div>
    <hr/>
    </div>



    <div class="inner row">
      <div class="right small">
        <%= image_tag 'makers/integration.png' %>
      </div>
      <div class="left big">
        <h2>Simple and fast hardware integration</h2>
        <p>
        Use the hardware you are familiar with like
          <a href="http://www.arduino.cc/">Arduino</a> (ethernet and Yun),
          <a href="http://www.raspberrypi.org/">Raspberry Pi</a>,
          <a href="http://electricimp.com/">Electric Imp</a>,
          <a href="http://spark.io/">Spark Core</a>,
          <a href="http://tiny-circuits.com/">TinyDuino</a>,
          <a href="http://netduino.com//">NetDuino</a>,
          <a href="http://mbed.org">mbed</a> and
          <a href="http://www.openpicus.com/">Flyport</a>
          or others giving you web connectivity.
          Lelylan supports <a href="http://mqtt.org/">MQTT</a> and lets you integrate any
          physical device by implementing few simple services. Connect your hardware to Lelylan,
          fire up the dashboard and get control of the physical world.
        </p>

        <%= image_tag 'hardware.png', class: 'bordered' %>
        <p><a class="button-add" href="http://dev.lelylan.com/getting-started#connect-your-first-light">Connect your first light &rarr;</a></p>
      </div>
      <div class="clearfix"></div>
    <hr/>
    </div>


    <div class="inner row">
      <div class="right small">
        <%= image_tag 'developers/apps.png' %>
      </div>
      <div class="left big">
        <h2>Apps for the Connected Home</h2>
        <p>
        Your products become part of a unified platform where devices communicate
        with each other and where services like <a href="http://ifttt.com">IFTTT</a>,
        <a href="http://twitter.com">Twitter</a> or
        <a href="http://www.google.it/glass/start/">Glasses</a>
        can be integrated. Create new apps related to web, mobile, energy saving,
        augmented reality, speech recognition, smart surfaces, neural based interfaces
        and anything else you like to work with. Start playing with the Connected Home
        and let <a href="http://twitter.com/lelylan">@lelylan</a> know about  your
        ideas and projects.
        </p>

        <p>
        <span class="button-add button-disabled">Lelylan Labs (coming 4Q 2014) &rarr;</span>
        <span class="button-add button-disabled">Lelylan Market (coming 1Q 2015) &rarr;</span>
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="clearfix"></div>
    <hr/>
    </div>


    <div class="inner row">
      <div class="left big">
        <h2>A structured solution</h2>
        <p>
        Lelylan describes the structure of any device using the concept of Types. For example
        we can have different lights (e.g. Lifx, Hue, etc) which uses different "languages"
        to communicate, but at the end (simplifying) they turn on and off. For this
        reason we created Lelylan Types, a place where you can find, create and discuss the
        structure of a device type which in its simplest form can be defined as the combination of
        three key elements.
        </p>

        <ul>
          <li>Properties - what vary during time.</li>
          <li>Functions - what a device can do.</li>
          <li>Statuses - what a device is in a specific time of its life.</li>
        </ul>

        <p>
        Defining the device type structure gives several advantages. Some are the possibility to
        automatically generate the device UIs, simulate the device behaviour when not connected
        to the physical world (perfect for app development) and standardize the structure of today's
        devices.</li>
        </p>

        <br><%= image_tag 'types.png' %><br><br>

        <a class="button-add" href="http://lelylan.github.io/types-dashboard-ng/">Get started with Lelylan Types &rarr;</a>
        <a class="button-add" href="http://dev.lelylan.com/types">Learn more about Types &rarr;</a>
      </div>
      <div class="right small">
        <%= image_tag 'makers/structured.png' %>
      </div>
      <div class="clearfix"></div>
    <hr/>
    </div>


    <div class="inner row">
      <div class="right small">
        <%= image_tag 'companies/cloud.png' %>
      </div>
      <div class="left big">
        <h2>Tools for selling connected products</h2>
